<br>
I'm new, but I've done a lot of research in this field. <br>
<br>
Just a few considerations should be made;<br>
<br>
1)  Einstein realised that light travelling through a vacuum (space) is the highest velocity for anything in the universe<br>
<br>
Therefore the speed of light through space is the cosmic speedlimit<br>
<br>
2) Time is the fourth dimension through which every 3Dimensional mass is moving through, its course through time is via what is known as a world line, <br>
<br>
Think of it as a basic three axes diagram with x=width, y=height and z=depth, m is the fourth axes=time, this axes however does not have a direction as such. The three dimensional object moves through this axes always! Therefore it never remains on the same position on the passage of time. <br>
<br>
3)   Gravity is a phenomenom that can influence the world line, a blackhole is the result of atoms collapsing within each other creating a gravitational field so powerful that not even light can escape, therefore in simple terms, its sucks in everything at the speed of light.<br>
<br>
At the event horizon all matter is blue shifted; accelerated. Therefore if a human was to approach one his atomic structure would accelerate i.e. his/her atoms and therefore be moving towards the speed of light. The closer one gets to the event horizon however, lets say foot first, then the atoms at his feet will be moving slightly faster then that of his head, so he'd be stretched getting longer and narrower as he approached, if he reaches the event horizon he'll be ripped apart.<br>
<br>
however the effect of nearing the speed of light will cause time dialation, I won't try to explain the reason cause It'll take all night, but basically lets say there's a black hole and Person a is within the gravitational field, person b is just outside the influence of the black hole and is watching a enter the hole. <br>
<br>
to b, As a got sucked in he'll appear to slow down until he comes to a stop, however b would experience normal time.<br>
<br>
To a, b would appear to accelerate and age until he dies and rots all within a few seconds, however a would experience normal time and reach the event horizon in those few seconds.<br>
<br>
If a was able to travel outwards from the black hole and EXCEDE the speed of light then he would defy the influence of the gravity of the black hole because nothing in the universe (natural that is) can excede the speed of light, but if he could! and he travelled a distance away from the hole to escape the gravitational influence, then he would find himself in the future, hundreds, thousands maybe even millions of years in the future depending on the distance and size of black hole.  <br>
<br>
but of course, this isn't really travelling to the future because you never really left the 'present', time was simply condensed. <br>
<br>
But the possibility of this happening is very slight due to our inability to excede the speed of light. <br>
<br>
As far as I know, (if I know anything) travel to the past is impossible because at any point an 3D object has a time-like direction, this direction is only to the future. We can't physically manipulate that direction. <br>
<br>
On a psychological basis, time might just be a product of the experience of consciousness. Passing from one present to the future, but then one must consider that we never can actually say we're in the future, can we...we're always in the present.<br>
<br>
I'm actually writing a comic that explores some of this, If all goes well, It'll be ready next year. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gaarasunakage>Gaara Sunakage</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.geocities.com/gaara_sunakage/Orochimaru.txt" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/10/03 1:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=12731.topic&index=47>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://godkodiak.homestead.com/files/Gaara1.jpg height=79 width=130></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ouch!</span><hr size=1> Agent Cryid, sure, that old lady in the dimension to the left of us, could have been i suppose a young man the first man to travel back through time in that dimension.<br>
