That seems to make sense. I've seen a few programs and read a few things about this, and some of them have mentioned that the passing (not flowing, i'm trying to use my words wisely) of time is merely a conscious perception; time is a singular position, and time travel would actually be a changing of &quot;coordinates&quot; on a plane; adhering to the 4th dimension concept, it would be much like X, Y, or Z.<br>
<br>
On parallel universes, I personally don't find it as convincing as an argument of 'condensing' time, but it also solves some uncertainties about time travel. My question concerns this:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Thirdly...If it were possable to &quot;time travel&quot; one theory says that you would not be able to alter the past but rather participate in the past in the line that you were meant to be there, raising the question, &quot;what shape is time?&quot; another theory is that yes you would be able to sort of time travel by jumping from one dimension that is slightly slower progression than ours but you face the possability of never returning to this dimmension and really what would it matter?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Concerning the paradoxical argument of eliminating yourself through ancestry... If the universe actually does occassionally split in two separate directions that parallel each other but are never alike nor simultaneous, then would it supposedly be possible to travel back in time (hypothetically), kill your grandfather, and thus cause another time-space split (or place you in one that already existed) that would lead you into another universe that paralleled the one you originated from but was not actually the same one? To make it a little simpler, would you be able to travel back to another point in time (the past), eliminate yourself in that universe, thus placing you in an alternate one, making return to your point of origin impossible? Just... expanding on this idea and trying to rule out the paradox.<br>
<br>
In a way, it kind of runs together with what was said earlier; that traveling into the future was possible, but would not allow for a return to your time of origin. It's an intriguing idea, but I'm not sure if it would actually work out that way.  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=shaolingundam01>Shaolin Gundam 01</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.geocities.com/millenia_optima/images/rbullet.txt" BORDER=0> at: 9/11/03 2:06 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=theandroid@polykarbonbbs>the android</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/12/03 12:05 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=12731.topic&index=50>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ouch!</span><hr size=1> Ah the paradoxes!!<br>
<br>
Time travel to the future is more plausible because it involves less paradoxes, travel into the past causes many.<br>
<br>
The grandfather paradox as it is refered to by authors can only be paradoctered if we consider that the universe constantly splits into parallel dimensions. But...consider this, there is a theory that states if a cat were put into a box with a bomb rigged to explode when opened, the event would only be determined if and when the box was opened, the possiblities are that the box explodes and the cat dies, or through some error the box does not explode and the cat lives. The universe will then split into two or more depending on the number of possible outcomes available to any given situation. therefore, parallel universes are actually lying at right angles from each other. this means there is a point at which the dimension began. <br>
<br>
Another theory states that skipping into another dimension would require a worm hole, as stated above (I forget by whom, apologies) thus our universe may just be a space-time bubble, the surface of which is a froth of quantum activity, from this froth sprout mini space-time bubbles and so on and so forth meaning that our universe is actually one of many space time bubbles of quantum processes. <br>
