<br>
Oop, you mean a different version of the multiverse theory. My mistake.<br>
<br>
Regarding opals question, Opal, decisions are NOT what split the universe. Quark positioning is. What does this mean?<br>
<br>
A quark is always in location A, or B, yet we have no way to determine where it is without measuring. There are no laws governing their position, that we know of at least. Some say quarks exist in both and neither until you measure, and force them into a position. Some simply say there are multiple universes for every quark location.<br>
<br>
This means there are infinite universes, some essentially identical, some radically different. We only exist in one of them however.<br>
<br>
<br>
I believe that's the flavour of the quantum multiverse that android was referring to <p><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><br>
